human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': "The UF Police Department removed three pro-Palestinian demonstrators from the Reitz Union Tuesday evening after they argued with a pro-Israel speaker inside. The protest came in response to a scheduled speaking event featuring Charlotte Korchak, an outspoken supporter of Israel. She gave a speech co-sponsored by UF Students Supporting Israel, UF Hillel and Stand with Us Israel. At least 75 students were in attendance. About 45 protestors gathered outside of the Reitz Union starting at 6 p.m. for what was advertised as a “Shut it Down for Palestine” event, organized by the Party for Socialism Liberation on Instagram. Some protesters’ signs read, “ceasefire” and “stop Zionist apartheid.” Protesters are not allowed to demonstrate inside buildings, according to university policy. The regulation was re-introduced in 2022 after a group of protesters entered Alumni Hall during UF President Ben Sasse’s Q&A forum. Several posters reminding students of the policy were taped to the door at least an hour before protestors arrived. Raymond Parker, a 25-year-old UF sustainable development master’s student and member of PSL, led the protest. “This should be a place for people to celebrate their cultures and heritages,” he said. “We don't want to create a space where some students feel very safe and some students feel as if their lives are being potentially threatened.” The last PSL protest Jan. 27 led GPD and UF Student Life to threaten student expulsions and arrests, according to PSL’s Instagram page. The increased tension from previous protest made this event even more important for Parker, he said. “We won’t be intimidated, we’re not gonna go away,” he said. After over an hour outdoors, the protestors entered the building, despite being aware of the policy. Protestors were allowed into the ballroom as long as they weren’t holding signs or causing disruption. “While speech is protected, disruptions inside university buildings are not, as university regulations clearly state,” wrote UF Spokesperson Cynthia Roldan in a statement. “We told them we would enforce the rules, and they decided they would break them and face the consequences.” When Korchak opened a Q&A session, eight protesters stood up and demanded a ceasefire in the conflict, striking an argument with Korchak. Korchak raised her voice many times, threatening removal, after being interrupted. “I don’t understand what you’re gaining from a [ceasefire] … this is my stage and you showed up … you can keep trying to act like you know what you’re talking about,” Korchak said. Raymond Parker was removed from the room by officers for disruption. Upon his removal, three protestors stood up with signs and started shouting in the ballroom, “ceasefire now, free free Palestine.” Two of those protesters — Tybee Wilcox, a 28-year-old Gainesville business owner, and Farrah Maswadeh, a 25-year-old Gainesville yoga instructor — were trespassed from campus for disrupting the event. Neither were affiliated with UF. Nobody was arrested. “I don’t believe any more of our tax dollars should go towards funding a genocide,” Wilcox said. “I believe in human rights for all.” According to their trespass ticket, they will be prohibited from entering all areas of UF grounds for three years. If they are seen on campus, they will be arrested. After her speech, Korchak said she knew about the protest beforehand. “I just wish they had come in and listened,” she said about the protesters. “I think the way we’re going to break the divide is listening to each other and having respectful dialogue and debate.” Amit Sapir, a 22-year-old UF biomedical engineering student who attended the speech, agreed and said he hoped the protesters gained something from the conversation. “I hope that both sides can educate themselves to reach a mutual truth,” he said. David Wygodski, a 19-year-old UF computer science freshman, attended the speech but had no knowledge of the protest happening outside. Seeing the protest made him angry, he said, but he feels more work needs to be done to reach a peaceful resolution between Israeli and Palestinian students. “Yelling at the top of your voice and leaving is not a good way to learn about this situation…we need to come together and sit down and listen to each other,” he said. Katherine Canev, a 19-year-old UF biochemistry freshman, attended the protest. “Palestinian persistence is huge to me,” she said. “It makes me feel good to see people and be with people who share the same views as me.” Contact Sara-James Ranta at sranta@alligator.org. Follow her on X @sarajamesranta. Sara-James Ranta is a third-year journalism major, minoring in sociology of social justice and policy. Previously, she served as a general assignment reporter for The Alligator's university desk."}]

the text is written entirely by a human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'TALLAHASSEE – The fate of the Senate’s sneak attack on public corruption investigations and the House’s push to disconnect kids from the internet are just some of the issues set to be decided as lawmakers clear the midpoint of the 2024 legislative session. A state budget for the year beginning in July is the only bill the Florida Constitution requires lawmakers to approve. Both the House and Senate are set to consider separate versions of a $115 billion-plus spending plan Wednesday, the 30th day of the scheduled 60-day session. But the homestretch of the session will involve settling an array of other proposals, including some like the Senate’s ethics legislation, which is drawing heightened focus. “This legislation would have a profound corrosive effect on transparency and accountability of government, in the form of precluding and preventing any ethics scrutiny on every level of both the state and local ethics commissions,” said Caroline Klancke, executive director of the nonprofit Florida Ethics Institute. Sen. Danny Burgess, R-Zephyrhills, last week unveiled new amendments to the ethics bill (SB 7014) that would prohibit both state and local ethics commissions from pursuing any investigation unless the complaint came from someone with "personal knowledge" of wrongdoing and willing to identify themselves by name and file under oath. Anything short of that would be considered hearsay, prohibiting commissioners from investigating potential ethical violations. The measure was approved 39-0 by the Senate. But critics say it is certain to undermine scores of complaints which often come from citizens who’ve read news stories about potential ethics violations or heard about them through second-hand sources. The idea of relying on a witness to wrongdoing stepping forward, swearing in and identifying themselves could eliminate much of the investigatory work of ethics panels, critics say. But Burgess defended his approach, saying it is “simply for fairness ... so somebody’s not just throwing (a complaint) out there. It has to be based on some form of merit.” Kirby Oberdorfer, director of Jacksonville’s Office of Ethics, Compliance and Oversight, told the Florida Times-Union that the legislation would make local ethics officials “lap dogs instead of watchdogs.” By raising the bar so high on complaints, ethics officials said most would likely never surface, shielding violators. While Senate President Kathleen Passidomo, R-Naples, said she saw no problem with the measure, House Speaker Paul Renner, R-Palm Coast, was less committal, saying only it’s “something we’re certainly going to look at.” In the session’s closing 30 days, the back-and-forth between the House and Senate will be critical to the fate of key priorities on both sides. After ignoring it for most of the session’s first half, the Senate added oomph to a Renner priority this week, with that chamber\'s Judiciary Committee approving a proposed ban on anyone under age 16 from having a social media account. The House bill (HB 1) already has won full approval there, but Monday’s Senate review was the first time that side had taken up Renner’s push. While Democrats have raised questions about the constitutionality of the measure – which many critics say violates the First Amendment right to speech – Renner and House Republicans are pressing for action. Last week’s appearance before Congress by Meta chairman and CEO Mark Zuckerberg on the impact of social media seems to have added loft to the Florida effort. But even Gov. Ron DeSantis, no stranger to promoting policies challenged on constitutional grounds, has questioned the “breadth” of the social media proposal. Similarly, in the session’s closing weeks, some level of agreement between the House and Senate also is needed on dueling approaches to proposed changes in child labor laws, education testing and standards, a big-ticket prison construction package and Passidomo’s priority, "Live Healthy," a plan aimed at improving Florida’s health care workforce and access to care by patients. Renner has vowed that his side will approve Live Healthy, even though it is only beginning to see light in the House after being approved by the Senate early in the session. “The Senate president and I are working together very well,” Renner recently said of his exchanges with Passidomo. But some measures look doubtful. Budget rolling along – but smaller: 2024 Session: Florida Legislature rolling back state spending in \'austere\' budget plans Senate has some ideas on school de-regs: Legislative session: Education deregulation bills OK\'d by Florida Senate, head to House House and Senate leaders have rebuffed efforts to revisit gambling legislation and create a provision setting the stage for Miami Beach’s Fontainebleau Hotel to open a casino. Jeffrey Soffer, developer of the hotel, has poured money into Republican lawmakers political committees and flew Gov. Ron DeSantis on his jet. While DeSantis appeared behind an effort to re-address state gambling laws to let Soffer obtain a needed pari-mutuel license, leaders have ruled it out. “My priority, and I think we’re all kind of on the same page, is that we get the Seminole (gambling) compact up and running, get it functioning well, and not stub our toe on something that would breach that – and there are some bills out there that I think would breach that,” Renner said, referring to the 2021 agreement with the state\'s Seminole Tribe. The state is expected to draw $500 million annually from the tribe, in exchange for giving it exclusive control of sports betting in Florida. Another push that may be sidetracked is the House’s effort to rollback to age 18 a ban on anyone buying a rifle or shotgun. The Senate so far has shown no interest in changing the current, 21-year limit approved after the killings at Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School in 2018. “It’s a non-starter for me,” Passidomo said last week. John Kennedy is a reporter in the USA TODAY Network’s Florida Capital Bureau. He can be reached at jkennedy2@gannett.com, or on Twitter at @JKennedyReport.'}]

'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'Subscribe for unlimited digital access to the news that matters to your community. by Ryan Paice | Be the first to comment The Anna Maria Charter Review Committee wasted no time in asking some major questions. At their first meeting, held Feb. 2 in chambers at city hall, CRC members discussed the merits of a city manager, decreasing the number of elected commissioners and increasing term lengths for commissioners and the mayor. The city must review its charter every five years by appointing a board of volunteers to comb through the document and presenting a slate of potential amendments to city commissioners for approval. Charter amendments are added to general election ballots as initiatives, so final approval falls to the city’s electorate. The city’s last charter review was done in 2019. This year’s CRC consists of five residents appointed by the city commission: Chris Arendt, Stevie Coppin, Scott Isherwood, Pat Olesen and Chuck Wolfe. Deputy clerk Fransheska Berrios, who is facilitating the charter review process this year, swore the appointees onto the board. Berrios then provided forms for members to nominate a chair and vice chair. However, the CRC members agreed that they were unfamiliar with each other and unable to provide informed nominations for the positions. Instead, they asked for someone to volunteer to serve as chair. Arendt stepped up and the committee unanimously voted to approve his appointment. Olesen was then unanimously appointed to serve as vice chairperson. City Commission Chair Mark Short, who was a member of the 2019 review committee, helped introduce the members to the review process. City attorney Becky Vose, who attended via speakerphone, also helped explain the process. Vose said the goal of the committee was to review the city charter for substantive changes, not stylistic, which she said included wording alterations like changing “happy” to “glad.” The CRC then took things from the top, beginning with Article I, “Creation and Powers,” which establishes the municipal government and its structure. They also reviewed Article II, “Corporate Limits,” but much of the committee’s discussion revolved around other matters. Olesen brought up the possibility of implementing a city manager form of government, which is when a professional manager is the city administrator. She said she did not know if it was a good idea or not, but she wanted to “throw it out there.” CRC members agreed to visit the topic during their review of Article III, “Legislative,” which details city elections, powers and processes. Wolfe suggested discussion on lowering the number of commissioners from five to three as the city has struggled with maintaining a five-member board. “We seem to appoint more than we elect with five members of the commission. So it seems like a legitimate question to ask whether we should have three members of the commission because that’s all we ever elect. Then we appoint people to fill the other two (seats),” Wolfe said. Asked his opinion, Short said he preferred a five-member commission for a more diverse representation of the community. Olesen said that if fewer people were interested in running for elected office, they could make it easier for those who stick around by increasing term lengths. Wolfe supported the idea, stating that the two-year election cycle seemed “onerous.” Arendt said they needed to find a balance for term lengths since he knew two past officials who were only interested in serving two years. CRC members agreed to circle back and continue the discussions on potentially decreasing the number of elected officials and increasing term lengths at a future meeting. There was no public comment and no members of the public attended the meeting. The charter review will resume with Article III, section 3.01, “City Commission, powers; composition,” at 1 p.m. Friday, Feb. 23, at city hall, 10005 Gulf Drive. Director General de la Policía Nacional dijo hoy que están trabajando los ascensos de los miembros de su institución y que en los mismos serán tomados en cuentas todos los ascenso que están atrasados de acuerdo a la ley interna de ellos que los rige. De igual manera el jefe de la policial informo también que serán tomados en cuentas conforme su ley interna para ascender a todos sus miembros de la institución del orden que se hayan graduados en las diferentes universidades. El Lic. Ramón Antonio Guzmán Peralta. Mayor General, P.N. director general de la Policía Nacional dio la información al momento de cuestionársele tanto a las Fuerzas Armadas como la Policía Nacional. ¿De cuál es la razón del porque estas instituciones violan sus propias leyes internas al no ascender a sus profesionales tan pronto se gradúan en cualquier curso técnico y/o Universitario en perjuicio de todos sus miembros? Además de demorar también el derecho de los ascensos que deben de ser cada cuatro años y no 5, 6 y 7 años, ascendiendo a otros con menos tiempos produciéndose allí lo que en dominicana se llama un cuello de botellas por los ascensos. El mas alto oficial policial emitió esta información al momento en que se llevaba a cabo la rueda de prensa la cual es ofrecida momentos después del tradicional encuentro de seguridad la cual hoy fue encabezada por el Señor presidente de la Republica Luis Rodolfo Abinader Corona, el Ministro de Defensa de la Republica Dominicana Teniente General Carlos Luciano Diaz Morfa. También ministro de Interior y Policía Jesús (Chu) Vásquez, el Jefe de Estado Mayor de la Fuerza Aérea de la República Dominicana Ingeniero Carlos Rodríguez Febrillet quien además es también es el Comandante Conjunto Unificado de las Fuerzas armadas, así como entre otras autoridades Militares. El presidente de la República, Luis Abinader, encabeza este lunes la reunión del Plan de Seguridad Ciudadana, donde se analizan los resultados de las estrategias implementadas para reducir los índices de criminalidad y delincuencia. Abinader fue recibido a las 11:08 de la mañana en la explanada del Palacio de la Policía Nacional. El jefe del Estado retoma esta habitual mesa de trabajo, luego de que el pasado lunes, 29 de enero, no se realizara debido al día feriado por el natalicio de Juan Pablo Duarte, uno de los padres de la Patria dominicana. Nuevo Comisionado El pasado 26 de enero, el Poder Ejecutivo designó, a través del Decreto 52-24, a Luis Ernesto García Hernández como el nuevo comisionado ejecutivo para Reforma Policial. García Hernández tiene entre sus funciones la implementación de los planes, estrategias y políticas de transformación y profesionalización del cuerpo de orden ciudadano. También, el presidente de la Dirección Nacional de Control de Drogas (DNCD), vicealmirante José Cabrera Ulloa, está presente en la sede policial. the text is written entirely by a human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'LAKELAND — McKeel Academy boys soccer coach Tanner Adams said after last week’s district championship win that he felt this was the most complete his team has been all year. The Wildcats are backing their coach up at just the right time. McKeel controlled every aspect of Tuesday night’s 4-0 Class 4A, Region 2 quarterfinal victory over Mulberry at Lane Construction Field. The Wildcats (17-3-2) dominated from start to finish, as they kept the Panthers (13-7-1) away from the ball and off the scoreboard. This was the ninth consecutive win for McKeel, which has seven shutouts in those nine wins and has outscored its opponents 32-2 during that stretch. “We’re always happy to win a game especially at this stage of the season,” Adams said. “I thought Mulberry kind of sat back and let us have more possession than I expected. I expected more pressure from them. It threw us for a bit, because by the first water break, we hadn’t scored. All it takes is one mistake. I feel like we’re at a point where if we get a goal, then with our possession game it’s more difficult to get it back off us. We’re hitting our stride a little bit as well.” After the teams battled to a 0-0 tie at the first water stoppage, Anthony Lucio banged home a nice cross from Drew Snyder for the first goal with 16:48 remaining in the first half. A little more than a minute later Harrison Weitz smacked a shot off the post that would’ve doubled McKeel’s lead. Hunter Mendez eventually got it to 2-0 with 8:15 left and that’s where the two teams stood heading into halftime. The second half was full of close calls by McKeel as Alexander Alejo, Snyder and Rico Zuniga all missed solid chances. Finally, with 12:38 left, Alejo hammered home a free kick from 20 yards out to make it 3-0. Snyder finished the scoring with 5:50 left, on another free kick between two defenders and the keeper. “That’s been the story for us all year,” said Adams, who led the Wildcats to the state final four last year. “We’ve created a bunch of chances, but we haven’t been able to score as much as we would like. As long as we continue to be patient and keep scoring goals, there’s good things to come,” “We just have to take it one game at a time.” Ella Williams scored off an assist from Mari Carr, and KJ Straub scored with an assist from Allie Williams to give Lakeland Christian a victory over The Pine School. Both goals came in the first half. Pine School (7-6-1) boasts perhaps the top player in the state in freshman Giovanna Waksman, who has scored 21 goals in eight games. However, she missed the game after being called up to the Brazil U-20 National Team. LCS advanced to regional semifinals and will play Jupiter Christian at home on Friday. Jupiter Christian defeated All Saints, 4-0.'}]

'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': "Headwind and I were in his carport, sorting dozens of flies that he’d found in a drawer full of zip bags in his office room, when a dented gray pickup stopped athwart the bow of his driveway. The bow is what Headwind calls the carport’s entrance. He calls the other end, at the garage door, the stern. He calls the sides port and starboard, all to remind visitors that in Biblical times he served in the Navy. “I think he does it mainly to remind himself,” Justin Casey says. “Headwind’s in that age bracket, y’know.” Speaking of Justin Casey, that was him in the dented pickup. He stepped down and shouted “Ahoy!” annoying Headwind. “Belay that. Speak plain English,” Headwind admonished him. “But you like using nautical argot,” Justin said. “I do,” Headwind said, “but I don’t like others using it.” Justin Casey’s known for being ready for anything. He always has at least two of everything, just in case he or somebody with him needs it. This makes him a popular member of the Fish or Cut Bait Society, well-known South Florida fishing club. You can test Justin in the real world: sneak a big rock aboard the boat and drop it over the side — splash! — when Justin isn’t looking. Shout something profane and say you just lost your rod and reel overboard in 300 feet of water. Justin will hand you a rod and reel. You’ll promise him you won’t drop them overboard. “If you do, I have another,” Justin will say. A lot of his spare fishing tackle is old stuff that still works, or that he thinks may work again in case he ever meets anyone who can repair it. Tiller, a modernist who is chairman of the steering committee, once took Justin Casey aside and tried to explain that there are no spare parts to fix his grandchildren's’ burned-out birthday candles that Justin saved. “I’m keeping them in case a friend needs them to wax his mustache” Justin asked. “Do you have a friend who waxes his mustache?” Tiller asked. Justin said not at the moment, but what if tomorrow? And what if he runs out of dubbing wax while tying flies? Justin is a child of the Great Depression, that time when the stock markets crashed. It was Oct. 24, 1929. People who woke up rich that morning went to bed poor that night. For the next five to 10 years, anyone who wasn’t starving or living in a refrigerator carton was made to feel guilty. “You had to salvage anything that broke or wore out,” Justin tells us. “It was a sin to throw stuff away because what if you or someone more needy, or more worthy, could use it? Not necessarily at that moment, but at any time in the next 100 years.” Headwind reminded us that he’s several years older than Justin. Of course he knows: “When my dad was a kid, his parents wouldn’t let him throw away rusted fish hooks because what if there was another world war? The metal might be needed to build military belt buckles.” Anyway, Justin is the reason for all those flies Headwind found in a drawer. Around 20 years ago, when he began tying his own, he made a lot of shaggy, ill-proportioned ones that he couldn’t have given away if he tried. Justin Casey persuaded him not to try, just in case there was another Great Depression and he couldn’t afford to buy flies. What if he caught arthritis and couldn’t tie his own any more? “Keep those flies for backups. They’re ugly but they’ll catch fish for you when you’re desperate,” he told Headwind. There’s hardly any space for Headwind in his own office. He bumps into and trips over stuff. He needs that drawer. Alone, it won’t solve his space and storage problem, but it’s part of a grander scheme. While re-disorganizing his garage, he discovered small amounts of space in several bins of flies. One bin contained several pocket boxes of trout flies from a trip to Patagonia in 2007. He knew then that he would return. He still doesn’t know when. Several more boxes contained landlocked salmon flies meant for Maine, where Headwind fished once or twice in the 1970s. Those flies, enticing streamers, might have served him well in Patagonia if he had remembered he had them — and where. I opened one of his baggies and found a lot of yellow and green freshwater streamers tied on saltwater hooks. “Great!” he cried. “Those are perfect for dolphin, also known as mahi mahi!” I asked when he last fished any of them. “I never did, because I forgot I had them,” he said. “Now that I remember, I will.” Another saltwater baggy contained a few flies tied on circle hooks. Headwind is pretty sure they are the first circle flies he ever tied. Now they’re in a box full of other circle flies that he uses a lot. Nobody else in the Fish or Cut Bait Society fishes circle flies, although Headwind has offered them around. He got the idea back when billfish tournaments started requiring contestants to use circle hooks with natural bait. Billfish don’t have teeth to bite their prey; they gulp it. A J-shaped hook is likely to snag harmfully in their gill rakers. A circle hook rolls back up to the mouth and snags in the jaw hinge. Headwind thought it might be a good idea for tarpon and snook, and he was right. Instead of yanking back on the fly line as soon as a fish bites, you simply press the line against the rod grip while the fish swims out the slack — usually about a second. It takes a while to get used to that, and most of us hate it because what is worse than losing a fish you’re going to release anyway? We’re trying to re-purpose as many of the trout and salmon flies as we can by adding weed guards. Headwind and I both like the full loop type. They’re easy to make when tying a fly, but a tedious pain in the rear to add to a fly already tied. Who do you guess taught us how to do that? Justin Casey did, and here he was. Headwind and I caught each other’s eyes, silently expressing the same idea. “This is a tedious pain in the rear,” I said, purposely adding a weed guard sloppily. “You’re embarrassing me. Give me that,” Justin said, and in the next couple of hours he turned a couple of dozen salmon flies into bass and peacock flies with full loop weed guards. Remember, all this work is part of the garage re-disorganization. You can’t tell at a glance, but Headwind has made a lot of progress. Without letting Justin Casey know, he got rid of a lot of old stuff he was never going to use again. Pretty soon, a lot of what’s crowding him out of his office will be moved to the garage. As you may guess, sorting flies is thirsty work. Headwind led us inside to the kitchen to collect three beers. With no malice aforethought, he set down a bin of flies that he’d forgotten he was carrying. “You will not stash that stuff in the kitchen!” his widow warned him. “Widow? I don’t have a widow,” Headwind said. “You will if you stash that stuff in the kitchen,” Mrs. Headwind said. Feedback: fishingdoer@gmail.com. Among the provisions of a gun safety bill in 2018 – reforms from the Parkland shooting massacre – was allowing the state more than three days to complete a background check for a prospective firearm purchaser. But that law could change under a measure that gun supporters want but critics don’t, saying the bill is dangerous. The proposal (HB 17) is sponsored by Panhandle-area Republican Joel Rudman. The bill is strongly supported by Gov. 2010 in Beijing, China. Sydney CNN — A Chinese-Australian author has received a suspended death sentence in China after five years on espionage charges, according to Australian Foreign Minister Penny Wong. Yang Hengjun, an Australian citizen and Chinese-born democracy activist, was sentenced by a court in Beijing on Monday, Wong said. ReportHe said the Australian government was “appalled” by the sentence. “We understand that if the individual does not commit serious crimes within a two-year period, this can be commuted to life imprisonment after two years,” Wong said. “This is heartbreaking news for Dr Yang, his family and all those who supported him. Our thoughts are with them. Yang, 58, was Arrested in 2019 at the airport when he arrived in the southern city of Guangzhou with his wife from New York to visit family in China. He later Accused of espionage – He has denied the allegations. Yang's case is shrouded in secrecy. Chinese authorities did not provide any details about his charges – including which country he was accused of spying for. In 2021, there was his trial Held behind closed doors Australian diplomats were denied access to a heavily guarded court in Beijing. Judgment and punishment were repeatedly delayed. China's court system is notoriously opaque — especially in cases involving national security — and the conviction rate is over 99%, according to legal observers. Yang has suffered ill health in detention. Last year, Yang said He feared he might die in prisonAfter a large cyst was discovered on his kidney. See also Spotify Wrapped 2023 brings you 'sound city' based on your music taste In her statement, Australian Foreign Minister Wong advocated for Yang with China “at every opportunity, and at the highest levels”. He pledged to continue to push for Yang's interests and well-being, including appropriate medical treatment, and to provide diplomatic assistance to him and his family. At a news conference on Monday, Wong said he called China's ambassador Xiao Qian to explain the sentence, while acknowledging it was “a decision of the Chinese legal system.” “All Australians want to see Dr Yang reunited with his family,” Wong said, adding that Yang had “options” to appeal the sentence. Yang's friend and former PhD supervisor in Australia, Feng Chongqi, called his punishment “a barbaric act by the Chinese Communist regime”. “Yang is being punished by the Chinese government for human rights abuses in China and for his advocacy of universal values \u200b\u200bsuch as human rights, democracy and the rule of law,” he said. “This is outrageous political persecution and the unacceptable arbitrary imprisonment of an innocent Australian citizen.” Feng also expressed concern about Yang's health, saying he is now “very ill”, and called on the Australian government to arrange medical parole for Yang and bring him back to Australia as soon as possible. Yang worked as an official in the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs before moving to Australia. Before his detention, he posted satirical comments critical of the Chinese government to his 130,000 followers on X, commonly known as Twitter. He also wrote a series of spy novels. 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'The waters off the coast of Flagler Beach had a 1,400-pound visitor on New Year\'s Day. A 13-foot great white shark named Breton pinged off the Flagler Beach at 1:34 p.m. Monday. Breton has been tracked by the research group OCEARCH since 2020, when a tag was attached to his dorsal fin in Nova Scotia. The tag transmits location information when Breton breaks the water\'s surface. Breton has been hanging around Florida for a bit, pinging off Jacksonville on Dec. 21 and previously visited Florida\'s east coast in June and December of 2022. He has traveled 8 miles in the past 72 hours and 33,969 miles since he was tagged, according to his tracker. Breton is known for making a \'self-portrait\' of sorts. His pings over a two-year period connect to show what looks like a massive shark. Here\'s what to know about Breton, OCEARCH and white sharks in Florida: Breton spent a little over two years making a "self-portrait." His pings between September 2020 and January 2022 connect to show what appears to be the outline of a huge shark, with the tail in Nova Scotia, the body along the east coast and head pointed at Florida\'s east coast. "You can track Breton, the white shark that made this self-portrait on the OCEARCH Global Shark Tracker," OCEARCH posted on X, formerly Twitter. Breton was the first shark tagged during OCEARCH\'s 2020 expedition in Nova Scotia, the group reported. At that time the adult shark was 13-foot, 3-inches long and weighed in at a whopping 1,437 pounds. Breton was named by SeaWorld, an OCEARCH partner, for the people of Cape Breton where he was tagged. White sharks swim south when the water gets too cold for them and they lack food sources up north, according to OCEARCH chief scientist Dr. Bob Hueter. Think of them as the snowbirds of sharks. Most of them tend to hang out away from the beaches in the continental shelf waters, Hueter said. OCEARCH is a nonprofit organization researching the ocean\'s giants. The group is recently finished up its 46th expedition, dubbed Expedition Southeast. It departed from Jacksonville on Nov. 17 and is made its final docking in Morehead City, North Carolina on Dec. 15. There are about 100 documented shark attacks around the globe each year and Florida is home to most of those. While Florida has the most attacks, South Africa has the most shark-related fatalities. Since 1992, there have been 1,234 shark bites worldwide, according to data from floridapanhandle.com, with white sharks credited as the top biters. Support local journalism by subscribing to a Florida news organization.'}]

Low 68F. Winds ESE at 5 to 10 mph.. Clear to partly cloudy. Low 68F. Winds ESE at 5 to 10 mph. Updated: June 1, 2024 @ 10:56 pm Staff with The Villages Recreation and Parks Department gather Thursday at Lake Okahumpka Recreation. The department received its CAPRA Accreditation Award and Certificate from the National Recreation and Park Association. The Villages Recreation and Parks Department is once again recognized as a gold standard in the nation. The National Recreation and Parks Association recently honored the department with its prestigious CAPRA Award — a distinction held by only 205 recreation and parks agencies nationwide. It is the third time the department has been presented with the association’s highest honor. It’s the award that means the most to John Rohan, director of The Villages Recreation and Parks. “There’s a lot of things that bring me much joy about what we’ve accomplished,” he said. “Achieving this national accreditation status provides additional validation to our agency and my 30 years of service to this profession. Our team is grateful for the support from the District administration, the Developer, our elected boards and residents during this process.” Providing first-class recreational opportunities to residents through an abundance of facilities and programming available in The Villages is what’s most important, Rohan said. “It’s mostly about being part of such a wonderful community of residents who embrace and support the vision of providing exceptional recreation and park services to help better their lives,” he said. Throughout 2023, the department went through an extensive review to show that it meets the highest level of standards and best practices in more than 150 categories such as mission, vision, relationships, planning, community involvement, organizational structure and fiscal responsibility. “Residents can be proud of the top-notch Recreation and Parks Department and team they have here in The Villages that is dedicated to providing lifestyle events and amazing facilities into the future,” said Kenny Blocker, District manager. The volume of recreation amenities and level of service provided by Recreation and Parks staff stood out to the accreditation committee, said Troy Houtman, director of Park and Recreation in Wichita, Kansas, who served as the leader of the review team. “The facilities were a standout, and the customer service is at the heart of the operations,” Houtman said. “This is a great accomplishment, and the community should be proud and supportive of the department.” Facilities What The Villages offers in recreation eclipses the number of amenities in most U.S. cities, according to data collected by the Trust for Public Land. With 253 pickleball courts, The Villages has 80 more courts than the top U.S. city — Honolulu, Hawaii, with 173 courts. There are more swimming pools in The Villages than any of the top 100 U.S. cities, according to the Trust for Public Land’s “City Park Facts” for 2023. The Villages has 113 swimming pools, of which 65 are adult pools, 36 are family pools and 12 are sports pools. In comparison, Chicago, the city with the next most, has 79 public pools followed by Philadelphia (72) and New York (66). Beyond pickleball courts and swimming pools, Rohan and his staff manage nearly 1,800 individual amenities at 116 recreation facilities including: • 15 softball fields at five complexes • 8 dog parks, with separate areas for small and large dogs • 7 fitness clubs at recreation centers, though membership fees apply. • More than 3,500 resident lifestyle clubs — with an equal number of residents serving as volunteer coordinators — meet at Villages recreation centers, and roughly 400 more residents coordinate outdoor sports activities. “The whole essence of this community is built on life and enjoyment and togetherness, and there is a synergy that exists where people want to engage and participate and interact,” Rohan said. Already in 2024, the department has welcomed the addition of the Hogeye Preserve Disc Golf Course, the first location for the sport in the community, and Cordoba Recreation, bringing a new resort-style family pool in addition to pickleball courts and corn toss to residents north of County Road 466. More new amenities are on the way to the northern area. A new game room is coming to La Hacienda Recreation, which will provide the first dedicated table tennis room in the community. Upcoming major renovations to Paradise Recreation will add 10,000 square feet of recreation space at the community’s original recreation center. Several recreation centers are in various stages of development in the Eastport area, south of Florida’s Turnpike. Olympia Recreation will bring four more softball fields and a new dog park. It also will be the first recreation center with an indoor gymnasium for pickleball, basketball, volleyball and a rock climbing wall. Other announced recreation centers on the way include Salukis, St. Tropez, Moultrie Creek, Shady Brooke, Oak Hollow, LaGrange, Lakeview and Waters Edge recreation centers. Programs Residents can enjoy and participate in a diverse list of recreation events offered by the department — including The Villages Senior Games, Camp Villages and The Enrichment Academy. The Villages Senior Games is an annual athletic event for individuals 50 and older that features sports including bowling, golf, pickleball, swimming, tennis, track and field and water volleyball. Camp Villages, another annual event, gives grandparents and their grandchildren the opportunity to participate in various activities together, such as arts and crafts, cooking classes, nature hunts, golf clinics and outdoor sports. Lisa Parkyn, lifestyles events manager for The Villages Recreation and Parks, said Camp Villages and The Villages Senior Games are two events that Villagers really embrace. “Camp Villages gives residents another reason to feel comfortable moving and living here, knowing that there are some options for when their grandchildren visit. I think most families and grandchildren are also impressed that there are all these opportunities,” Parkyn said. “When it comes to Senior Games, we have the facilities and the great area to host everything, where other communities do have to piecemeal together where they’re going to have some of their competitions.” The Enrichment Academy, which has been around since 2017, offers Villages residents a chance to expand their educational horizons. The adult education program is split into fall/winter and spring/summer semesters, with about 300 fee-based courses offered each semester for residents and the public in multiple subjects, including art, music, health and wellness, sports, language, travel, dance, writing, culinary, crafts, history and technology. “The Enrichment Academy is dedicated to offering innovative, quality programming,” said Melanie Sarakinis, recreation manager with the academy. “New instructors and courses are added each semester.” In addition to courses, residents can enjoy educational lectures each month through the program’s Speaker Series. “These cover different topics,” Sarakinis said. “We bring in global speakers about historical events, innovative technologies and experiences to share with the community.” Managing Editor Keith Pearlman can be reached at 352-753-1119, ext. 5347, or keith.pearlman@thevillagesmedia.com. February 05, 2024 at 01:58 PM 4 minute read Judges Santo DiGangi, a partner at Critton, Luttier & Coleman, was at his desk in his law firm’s West Palm Beach office when he saw an 850 number pop up on his phone. “My heart raced, and I heard the news that I was appointed, and it was without question the best call I’ve ever received in my professional career,” DiGangi said. “I called my wife, and it was overwhelming. This is something I’ve dreamed of for a long time.” DiGangi, whom Gov. Ron DeSantis appointed to the Palm Beach County Court, will fill the vacancy created by the elevation in October of Judge James Sherman to the Palm Beach Circuit Court. In an interview, DiGangi said he intends to run an orderly courtroom. “The way I go about my practice, I am civil, and I treat every opponent I have with respect in the courtroom,” DiGangi said. “I hope that is the same demeanor I see before me.” Now, DiGangi is winding down his busy legal practice and is set to begin his service on the bench on March 1 in the civil division. DiGangi is the son of immigrants, who were both born in Sicily, Italy, and immigrated to the U.S. to pursue the American dream. DiGangi was born in New York City, and according to his mother, he knew he wanted to be a lawyer when he was a 5-year-old. “I used to carry my dad’s briefcase around the house and said I was a lawyer,” DiGangi said. However, DiGangi experienced heartbreak at a young age. His father, an attorney in Italy who did not continue his practice in the U.S., died from cancer when his son was age 9. Soon after, DiGangi and his mother moved to West Palm Beach. DiGangi went on to earn his undergrad and law school degrees from the University of Florida. After the Florida Bar admitted DiGangi to the practice of law in October 2009, he clerked for the Palm Beach Circuit Court for over a year and a half before joining the Miami-Dade State Attorney’s Office as an assistant state attorney. DiGangi was tasked with prosecuting felony criminal cases in which he tried around 25 jury trials and over 100 bench trials. However, DiGangi said he wanted to return to West Palm Beach, and chance would have it that his former boss at the Palm Beach Circuit Court told him he would be a great fit at Critton, Luttier & Coleman. A key selling point to DiGagi was that the law firm was adamant about giving back to the community. Greg Coleman, then the president-elect of the Florida Bar and a partner at the law firm, told DiGangi that he was looking to hire an associate. Following a meeting, Coleman hired DiGangi in September 2013. DiGangi has since focused his practice on complex commercial litigation, personal injury, wrongful death, complex probate and trust litigation, and legal malpractice. A couple of months later, DiGangi met his wife, with whom he now has three children, before a football game between the University of Florida and the University of Georgia. “Our tagline is that we fell in love at a tailgate,” DiGangi said. Meanwhile, about seven years later, the law firm promoted DiGangi to partner. Still, DiGangi said he wanted to devote more time to public service. When DiGangi received the call of his appointment, he said it was a full-circle moment. “My first job out of law school was as a law clerk at the Fifteenth Circuit, with some of the judges who are now going to be my colleagues,” DiGangi said. “I am so thrilled to be returning to the same place where I started my career and serving the people in my hometown.” NOT FOR REPRINT © 2024 ALM Global, LLC, All Rights Reserved. Updated: June 16, 2024 @ 8:18 pm The Supreme Court on Friday struck down a Trump-era ban on bump stocks, the rapid-fire gun accessories used in the deadliest mass shooting in modern U.S. history, in a ruling that threw firearms back into the nation’s political spotlight. “Republicans are the party of Abraham Lincoln, but Black people are stuck on the Democratic plantation.” Red Lobster, which abruptly closed more than 50 restaurants last month, revealed in bankruptcy court that it could close at least 125 locations as it tries to recoup losses from its endless shrimp promotion. The nation's largest festival showcasing films by people of African descent returns this week for its 28th year with some of the country's hottest talents congregating here in South Florida. Among them: actor Denzel Washington, filmmaker Ava DuVernay and actress and writer Issa Rae. Florida faces an elevated risk of mosquito-borne illnesses due to early forecasts predicting a rainy year ahead, following historic outbreaks in the previous year, with officials emphasizing the crucial role of mosquito control efforts to mitigate health threats. Early forecasts warn of a rainy, wet year ahead, providing an ideal environment for mosquitoes to grow and thrive and creating increased risk for humans of contracting a mosquito-borne illness. This warning, shared at a recent press conference, comes after historic mosquito-borne illnesses last year, including Florida’s largest dengue fever outbreak in more than 75 years and the first locally transmitted case of malaria in the state in more than 20 years. “These public servants are unsung heroes,” said Brandon area Sen. Jim Boyd, referring to mosquito control workers. “The potential health threat to tens of millions of Floridians and visitors is dramatically reduced by mosquito control professionals who deploy high-tech tools, scientific research and 24/7 work in the air and on the ground.” He reiterated warnings of increased mosquito activity and associated health risks. “But I rest easy, and Floridians can too, knowing our state has the nation’s best mosquito-control teams working to protect our health and our economy,” Boyd added during last week’s remarks. The Florida Mosquito Control Association (FMCA) includes 15 independent mosquito control districts throughout the state, with elected boards that work with Florida’s 42 county and municipal mosquito control programs. Each year, representatives from the group travel to Tallahassee during the legislative session to advocate for their work, and for resources needed to complete it. “We are proud to work with so many partners including local health departments and local officials,” said Phil Goodman, FMCA board member and chair of the Florida Keys Mosquito Control District. “But one of the biggest reasons for our success in controlling mosquitoes is the constant collaboration between mosquito control programs and districts. Whether it’s Pensacola or Miami or anywhere in between, we work as one statewide unit when it comes to ensuring we are all doing our best work to keep our state healthy and our economy booming.” Mosquito-borne illness is nothing new in Florida – scientists have been educating the public about risks for more than a century – but the risks remain, including from Zika, West Nile virus, chikungunya virus and dengue fever. “As a practicing physician in the Florida Keys I have seen firsthand the detrimental effects of what a simple mosquito bite can do to the human body,” said Stan Zuba, a pediatrician and Florida Keys Mosquito Control District board member. “Due to Florida’s tropical and subtropical climates, we have to remain vigilant all year-round – using appropriate protections and repellants while outdoors, especially during the dawn and dusk hours when mosquitoes are most active.” Also present at the press conference were members of the Legislature and Bob Lotane, a Tallahassee resident who in 2014 contracted West Nile Virus after being bitten by a mosquito. He cautioned Floridians to remain vigilant, retelling his experience with the illness and urging others to protect themselves and their loved ones. 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'By Marci Shatzman Do you still look like the picture on your Florida driver’s license? I didn’t anymore. The photo was at least 10 years old, when I was still dying my hair brown with blonde highlights. I’ve had white hair for seven years and avoiding Covid had nothing to do with it. I just wanted to save a pile of money and the time it took to dye it. I’m sure the state thought they were doing us all a favor when they used the same photo they had for years, and didn’t require a new license until 2028. And nobody minds looking younger than they are. But I’m 77 now, and the only thing still recognizable on my license photo was my smile. So, I kept the license as is, but then two things happened that changed my mind. I tried to update an online account that required me to take a selfie and an image of my driver’s license. The answer was something similar to phishing, faking who you are online. That company refused to believe the new me was me. And worse-case scenario, the next time I traveled, my first trip after Covid, I would probably be stopped and pulled aside at the airport for impersonating me. Who wants to risk that? So, I made an appointment to replace my driver’s license at the Palm Beach County Tax Collector’s facility on Congress Avenue in Delray Beach. You can’t just show up. You have to make an appointment and you can do that online at this link: My appointment was less than a week later, and I only had to wait about 20 minutes longer. When my number was called, I told the customer service rep I wanted to replace my license. He had me pose against a portable white screen at his station for the photo, and I handed him my old license. I got both back. The whole process took minutes and cost $38.10. Best photo I ever took and money I ever spent. learn their lesson,” the source told MargateNews.net. _______________________ On the MPD 27 years, Captain Joe Galaska was appointed Interim Police Chief to replace former Police Chief Jon Shaw, who was terminated in December 2021 for sexually charged allegations. The investigation into Shaw revealed the former Chief sexting on duty and sending explicit photos to a subordinate. In Galaska’s case, we’re told that the Chief first shared text(s) with a male colleague, who then shared them with a female colleague. From there, the text circulated among higher ups. While Galaska’s offense does not rise to that of Shaw’s, said the source, it’s nonetheless reckless and represents bad judgement. The same source, a Margate police officer for more than 20 years, said that unhealthy cliques have evolved in the department and are negatively impacting the work environment. “Everyone is jockeying for power and stabbing each other in the back,” the source said in a phone call. City commissioners agreed to hire an independent firm to investigate allegations against Galaska. Few details were released at the December meeting and names were kept confidential. The allegation was serious enough to assign a third-party firm to the case. This in the wake of Margate’s own internal affairs unit compromising the Shaw case, according to a separate administrative report. Galaska is the third Margate Police Chief in five years under scrutiny for hostile work environment. Shaw’s predecessor, former Police Chief Dana Watson, was sued by a former Margate Police officer in 2015. The officer claimed Watson and others conspired to terminate him for attempting to out racism and unprofessional behavior in the MPD. The jury in the case agreed, but their decision was reversed in an arbitration hearing when Watson went on record as saying he didn’t care what a jury of six thought. Jon Shaw Update Elected officials will attend yet another shade meeting over the fate of a lawsuit filed by former Police Chief Jon Shaw who was terminated in December 2021 for sexually charged allegations. The former Chief seeks $36,000 in accrued personal leave that he said he is owed. The city says otherwise. All of this is in court records (CACE-22-015492) filed in 2022 that show the city paid Shaw severance, along with unreimbursed accrued sick leave and unreimbursed accrued vacation pay after he was terminated. Though his offenses were egregious (as evidenced by the investigation to out him) Shaw claims in his lawsuit that he’s entitled to personal leave based on a PBA union agreement that puts him leaving his position in good standing. Shaw was a 24-year veteran of the Margate Police Department. The shade meeting takes place Tuesday at 4 p.m. at City Hall. The meeting is briefly open to the public and then closed for commission deliberations in private. The meeting comes as Shaw introduces a counteroffer. The next scheduled hearing between parties is mediation by February 29th. If that fails, parties will prepare for a jury trial in April.'}]

Así, ha manifestado que el exmandatario chileno “defendió a su nación en el escenario mundial”, según un comunicado publicado por la Casa Blanca. “Durante la pandemia de COVID-19, puso la seguridad de sus conciudadanos por encima de todo, ayudando a Chile a lograr una de las tasas de vacunación más rápidas del mundo”, ha recordado. “Tras el devastador terremoto y tsunami de 2010, el firme liderazgo de Piñera no sólo ayudó a Chile a avanzar a través del dolor de la oscuridad y la pérdida, sino que permitió a Chile emerger con más fuerza, una inspiración de la que los chilenos pueden seguir sacando lecciones a día de hoy mientras luchan con valentía y se recuperan de los trágicos incendios forestales”. “Aprecio profundamente mi tiempo de trabajo con Piñera durante la última década, cuando vi de primera mano su dedicación a su país y a nuestra asociación. Estados Unidos mantendrá el importante legado de cooperación que ayudó a pergeñar y enviamos nuestras profundas condolencias a la ex primera dama Cecilia Morel, su familia y todos los que lamentan esta gran pérdida”, ha zanjado. Por su parte, Putin ha trasladado al presidente de Chile, Gabriel Boric, sus “profundas condolencias” por la “trágica muerte” de Piñera. “Habiendo ocupado en dos ocasiones el puesto de jefe de Estado, Sebastián Piñera hizo mucho por el desarrollo socioeconómico del país y contó con una gran autoridad internacional”, ha reseñado, según un comunicado del Kremlin. De esta forma, ha hecho hincapié en que el exmandatario chileno “hizo una contribución significativa a nivel personal para el desarrollo de unas relaciones amistosas entre Rusia y Chile” y ha ahondado en que “tuvo la oportunidad de comunicarse en persona con este destacado estadista” y en que “siempre preservará un gran recuerdo de él”. Piñera, de 74 años, falleció en un siniestro de helicóptero que tuvo lugar minutos después del despegue del aparato, pilotado por él mismo. Las autoridades no han determinado aún las causas, a la espera de que avance la investigación. De la aeronave lograron salir los otros tres pasajeros –su hermana Magdalena, su amigo y antiguo socio Ignacio Guerrero y el hijo de este último–, que llegaron por sus propios medios hasta la orilla y sin daños relevantes. As spring break kicked off, college students rushed to Florida beaches for a week of partying and relaxation. But the idyllic image of spring break fails to resonate with everyone. Beaches are left littered, crime spikes and excessive partying disrupts some students who are looking for a laid back beach day at home. If a poet, athlete, music enthusiast and novice ping pong player were gathered into a room, it may seem like they wouldn't have much in common. The UF cheerleading team currently has 13 men and 24 women, divided into a combination of male-female stunt pairs and all-girl groups. The athletes spent most of the two-hour practice preparing for next month’s cheer tryout, during which they’ll do their best to recruit talented newcomers — and show up themselves to re-earn their spots on the team. But tryouts will be less competitive for some than others. The winner of the Florida Invitational Step Show’s Stroll Off competition, Kappa Alpha Psi fraternity, is focusing on its community and celebrating Black culture — despite an arrest that occurred at the event last weekend. The Divine Nine promote academic excellence for African American students on predominantly white campuses. It also provides them with a space to address pertinent issues within the Black community, said Ammir Thomas, vice president of Theta Sigma Chapter of Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity. In 2023, the UF Police Department had 122 cases of registered bike theft. That’s 60% higher than the previous year, which saw 76 thefts. The numbers for registered cases in the preceding years were 76 in 2022, 84 in 2021, 130 in 2020 and 104 in 2019, even with the effects of COVID-19. Black UF students form strong bonds through diverse campus organizations at the predominantly white university. David Canton, UF director of African American studies, calls it the “eyeball test.” For vegan students like Maxine Sculthorpe, an 18-year-old UF biomedical engineering freshman, walking into a new dining hall can be intimidating because her food options are frequently limited to meager portions and subpar substitutes, she said. Every semester, a small group of students have the opportunity to play the Century Tower Carillon — an instrument made of bells — ranked among one of the largest university carillons out of the less than 200 nationwide. Since the carillon’s first recital in 1979, each student’s performance is an addition to the tower's historic legacy and unique sound, according to its website. With a prominent LGBTQ+ community at UF, including the UF Pride Student Union and the UF LGBTQ+ Alumni Association, gendered housing can be a difficult experience for many students on campus. Out of 26 residence halls on campus, UF only has one gender neutral housing option — the Lavender Living Learning Community, located in Springs Residential Complex, hopes to create a more inclusive and diverse housing experience. Students’ first impressions of the temporary dining hall included “eating in the trenches,” “an interesting experience” and “kind of cute” since its opening Jan. 6. The climate-controlled Norman Field structure will serve UF students while The Eatery at Broward Hall undergoes a full renovation. In the past two years, the areas surrounding Gainesville campuses saw both the Thanksgiving weekend shooting and the shootings at The Crossing. Both UF and Santa Fe College received hoax school shooting threat calls in 2023 as well. Both UF and Santa Fe College students have concerns about campus safety. The start of every semester brings about a new wave of academic goals and resolutions, with students scrambling to find the best tips and tricks for productivity. While there’s no doubt that building healthy study habits is important, finding the perfect space to implement those habits is just as important."}]

"PLACE YOUR LEGAL NOTICES HERE PALATKA, Fla., Feb. 2, 2024 — The St. Johns River Water Management District is conducting a 92-acre prescribed burn today at Newnans Lake Conservation Area in Alachua County. The burn’s purpose is to reduce hazardous fuel loads and maintain fire-dependent natural communities. Prescribed fire is the use of carefully planned fire purposefully set under stringent conditions to manage the fire's effects. Before conducting a burn, the District ensures that wind and other weather conditions are correct for managing the fire and minimizing the impacts of smoke to residents and traffic. Periodic prescribed fires on District lands enhance the land’s environmental quality and protect its neighbors from destructive wildfires, but not without the possibility of temporary nuisances, such as smoke and ash. Prescribed fires help prevent wildfires by burning off fuels that naturally build up over time, while also helping to manage the growth of woody shrubs. In fire-dependent ecosystems, fire is nearly as important as rainfall and sunshine. The benefits of prescribed fire include restoring and maintaining natural communities, reducing chances of destructive wildfires, perpetuating fire-adapted plants and animals, cycling nutrients, managing tree diseases and opening scenic vistas. Follow the District on social media to know when prescribed burns are taking place in your area. To learn more about the District’s prescribed burn program, visit the District online at www.sjrwmd.com/lands/management/prescribedfire or follow the conversation at #LoveYourLands #RxBurn #goodfire #sjrwmd. # # # Email editor@ alachuatoday.com"}]

Readers are encouraged to comment or submit a Letter to the Editor to share their opinions. To submit a Letter to the Editor, follow the instructions here. The conservative crusade against all things “woke” has claimed another victim. On Jan. 2, Claudine Gay, Harvard University’s first Black president, resigned due to the fallout from her statements on antisemitism and accusations of plagiarism. At six months and two days, her tenure as president was the shortest in the school’s almost 390-year history. The backlash from prominent conservatives helped fan the flames of her demise, but let’s linger on the two main issues for a moment. In the closing moments of the Dec. 5 congressional hearing, Rep. Elise Stefanik (R-NY) asked a question: “Does calling for the genocide of Jews violate Harvard’s rules on bullying and harassment?” To this inquiry, Gay responded, “It can be, depending on the context.” That’s it. This 10-second interaction is why Harvard’s 30th president is now unemployed. Gay is entirely correct here; any potential disciplinary outcome would rely solely on the context of the situation. What I find insidiously genius about Stefanik’s question is that it did two things—first, it framed an incredibly nuanced question as a simple yes-or-no, and second, it masked a question about free speech as one about antisemitism. If Gay were to say “yes,” she would be both lying and setting a broad precedent for how to apply Harvard’s code of conduct. If her answer were “no,” she would also be lying and framed as antisemitic and unsupportive of Jewish students. However, because the question addresses the issue of free speech on campus, she had to say that it depends on context because issues regarding speech have always depended on their contexts. This is the trap Stefanik laid out for Gay. Honestly, it’s a perfect way to audition herself as Trump’s potential running mate. As for the accusations of plagiarism, the evidence is about as structurally sound as a house of cards. A few “instances of inadequate citation” and “duplicative language without appropriate attribution” (both of which she later corrected) in a 1997 doctoral dissertation seem like another example of conservative critics grasping for straws. While Gay doesn’t have the most substantial academic catalog, these accusations should’ve been of no concern to anyone. The resignation of Gay is the Republican Party’s latest victory in their war against the education system. For nearly two years, conservatives have waged this war on our nation’s schools, colleges and universities. From Alabama to Wyoming, Republican politicians across the country are on a mission to eradicate all things “woke” (still don’t know what that means) from our learning institutions. Unfortunately, the Republicans are winning this battle. Our schools will no longer serve as bastions of learning or free speech and expression if conservatives continue to have their way. To save our learning institutions, they must refuse to capitulate to the pressures of conservative outrage and their manufactured, politically motivated culture war on “woke.” ___ For more information or news tips, or if you see an error in this story or have any compliments or concerns, contact [email protected]. the text is written entirely by a human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'TAMPA — Joe Chillura Jr., architect and longtime elected official who crafted a half-penny sales tax that built a football stadium and went on to pay for billions in community improvements, died Saturday. He was 84. He died peacefully in his sleep from natural causes, according to a spokesperson for the family. Chillura was a true son of Tampa, born in Ybor City, raised in Seminole Heights and a 1958 graduate of Hillsborough High before he went on to the University of Florida to study architecture. His mother worked in a cigar factory, and his father was a partner in a construction firm that built local schools. Chillura, a Republican, was elected to the Tampa City Council in 1970, served 12 years on the Hillsborough planning commission and eight more as a Hillsborough County commissioner in the 1990s. He played a pivotal role in crafting the Community Investment Tax in the 1990s — which was controversial because it used public money to pay for Raymond James Stadium for the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. The tax also funded schools, parks, fire stations, public safety investments, libraries and other community needs. “It was so important, not just for the stadium,” former Tampa Mayor Dick Greco, who knew Chillura since childhood, said Tuesday. “The schools were about to go on double sessions.” In a 2021 Tampa Bay Times interview, Chillura compared the tax to the old Sweet Tomatoes buffet restaurant on Dale Mabry Highway near the stadium, known for its vast array of food choices. “I said, ‘You know what, that concept could fly for a tax where everybody gets a little bit of something,’” he said, “even if they don’t like the other something.” The tax passed in 1996 with 53% of the vote. “He stuck his neck out,” said Tampa political consultant Victor DiMaio, a longtime friend. “He took a lot of heat for it at the time.” Through fiscal year 2022, the tax has generated $2.6 billion. As it reaches its 30-year sunset, the County Commission is considering whether to put its renewal on the November ballot for voters to decide. “But he never boasted about it, never said, ‘Oh, I did this, I did that,’” Greco said. “A very quiet, very nice person. Not what you see in politics today.” Subscribe to our free Stephinitely newsletter Want more of our free, weekly newsletters in your inbox? Let’s get started. Chillura also championed the Neighborhood Bill of Rights, advocated for the Landmarks Ordinance for Historic Preservation and helped establish the Hillsborough County Economic Development Department. In 1972, he helped draft an ordinance to make downtown Tampa greener. The Planning Commission gave him its Person of Vision Award. Chillura often encouraged others to get involved in community matters and politics. To the end, he remained deeply concerned about Tampa’s shrinking tree canopy. “Joe had a lot of perseverance. If he made up his mind to get something done, he made it happen,” said his wife Mary Helen Chillura in a news release. “He wanted to make Tampa a better place, and I think he did that.” Chillura ran for Congress in 1998 but lost to Jim Davis. The Chillura name endures in Tampa. A busy public park across from the downtown courthouse is named Joe Chillura Courthouse Square, site of gatherings, protests and work lunches. His family is involved in local banking, and his grandson Max Chillura owns five Chill Bros. ice cream shops around town. Known for his affability, Chillura regularly held court at the West Tampa Sandwich Shop at his same table to the right of the door. Regulars, Republicans and Democrats alike, would quietly read their newspapers over cafe con leche, and then the ribbing would begin, DiMaio said. Another regular was the late Jack Espinosa, a former comedian and sheriff’s office spokesperson with a slapstick style. Across the table, Chillura was the opposite, his barbs dryer and more subtle. “I miss some of that give and take,” DiMaio said. “Joe was from the old school.” He is survived by his wife of 60 years, Mary Helen, a teacher at Berkeley Preparatory School; five children: Tina, Joe, Conna, Paul, and Vincent; and grandchildren, Christopher, Avery, Patton, Max, Hadley, Nash, Audriana, Adaline, and Annalise. He is survived by his sister, Mary Diecidue. A Mass will be held Thursday, Feb. 8, at 2 p.m. at Christ the King Church, 821 S. Dale Mabry Highway, with the family receiving friends from 1-2 p.m. That will be followed by a celebration of life outside Armature Works near Oak & Ola restaurant. Instead of flowers, the family asked for donations to St. Peter Claver School or Villa Madonna School. “We’re going to miss him,” Greco said. “But at least he lived a wonderful life.” Sue Carlton is an urban affairs reporter, covering Tampa’s ongoing development. She can be reached at scarlton@tampabay.com. The Tampa Bay Times e-Newspaper is a digital replica of the printed paper seven days a week that is available to read on desktop, mobile, and our app for subscribers only. To enjoy the e-Newspaper every day, please subscribe.'}]

Yoni Buckman Report: Less than 250,000 Holocaust survivors still live; 18% in North America Fewer than 250,000 Holocaust survivors remain alive today, according to an unprecedented new report by the organization that has sought to ensure that they are compensated for their suffering. The oldest known survivor, according to the Conference on Jewish Material Claims Against Germany, is New Yorker Rose Girone, who turned 112 last month. She and her family fled Nazi Germany for Shanghai, where they endured terrible conditions before making their way to the United States. “My mother will be the first to tell you, we’re very lucky all around,” said her daughter Reha Bennicasa, who at 85 is just below the median age of survivors today (86). The Claims Conference has long shared basic information about who is receiving the aid it negotiates annually with Germany and offered a similar number of estimated survivors last year. But the new demographic overview is the first to break down the population of Jewish survivors by country of birth and current country of residence; age; gender; and the percentages receiving various compensations and services. It identifies survivors in more than 90 countries: 49 percent reside in Israel, 18 percent in North America, another 18 percent in Western Europe; and 12 percent in the former Soviet Union. The youngest are on the cusp of 80 – the war ended in 1945 – and 61 percent are women. The organization says the statistics show that the work of helping survivors is far from over. “Now is the time to double down on our attention on this waning population,” said Gideon Taylor, president of the Claims Conference. “Now is when they need us the most.” Your email address will not be published.
